4. Data Preprocessing

There is no missing value in the dataset. Among the 1599 observations, 240 rows were duplicated entirely. Considering the 12 physicochemical properties variables are all at two decimal point precision, the likelihood of a complete duplicate existing in real life is low, so we removed these observations from the analysis. This study also combined Mahalanobis, Leverage, and Cooks Distance to define and remove 62 outliers rows, leaving 1297 observations in the dataset.

4.4 Removing outliers

4.4.1 Mahalanobis

#calculate the mahalanobis distances for each row in the data

mahal <- mahalanobis(wine_data_1, 
                     colMeans(wine_data_1), 
                     cov(wine_data_1))
#calculate the cutoff value by calculating the quantile of the  Chi-squared distribution based on the strict significance level of 0.001 and the degree of freedom as the number of variables/columns
cutmahal <- qchisq(1-.001, ncol(wine_data_1))

badmahal <- as.numeric(mahal > cutmahal) ##note the direction of the > 
table(badmahal)
## badmahal
##    0    1 
## 1306   53

4.4.2 Leverage

#To get the other outlier statistics, we have to use the regression model we wish to test. And in this case, we will use the lm() function with our regression formula.)
mod_1 <- lm(quality ~ ., data = wine_data_1)

k <- 11 ##number of IVs
leverage <- hatvalues(mod_1)
cutleverage <- (2*k+2) / nrow(wine_data_1)
badleverage <- as.numeric(leverage > cutleverage)
table(badleverage)
## badleverage
##    0    1 
## 1259  100

4.4.3 Cook’s Distance

cooks <- cooks.distance(mod_1)
cutcooks <- 4 / (nrow(wine_data_1) - k - 1)
badcooks <- as.numeric(cooks > cutcooks)
table(badcooks)
## badcooks
##    0    1 
## 1277   82

4.4.4 Combined methods

### Table with total score for the number of indicator that the data points have
totalout <- badmahal + badleverage + badcooks
table(totalout)
## totalout
##    0    1    2    3 
## 1211   86   37   25
wine_nooutliers <- subset(wine_data_1, totalout < 2)

The dependent variable in this study is Quality. Quality ranges from 3 to 8, mostly around 5 and 6.

The wine quality data is nearly normal distributed and confirmed further by calculating the skewness and kurtosis values.

Skewness measure a degree of asymmetry of data distribution that deviates from the symmetrical normal distribution. The value of skewness at 0.2 shows that the data are nearly symmetrical as 0 indicating normal distribution.

Kurtosis measures the heaviness of a distribution’s tails relative to a normal distribution. Since the standard normal distribution has kurtosis of 3, the calculated value of Kurtosis is 3.3 just slightly higher than 3 indicating a slightly positive Kurtosis, or leptokurtic

5.2 Evaluating independent variables

The 11 independent variables are mostly skewed to the right. Four properties showed an interesting relationship between the variable value and the quality score. Citric Acid, Alcohol, and Sulphates indicate a positive relation-ship with quality, showing that the higher these variables are, the higher the quality score. Meanwhile, volatile Acidi-ty presents a negative relationship with quality.

5.2.1 Fixed acidity

box_hist_plot<- function(column) 
  {
  boxplot_var<- ggplot(wine_nooutliers, aes(x = quality, y = .data[[column]], fill = factor(quality))) +
    geom_boxplot(color = "black") +
    ggtitle(paste(toTitleCase(column), "vs Quality")) +
    xlab ("Quality") +
    ylab (toTitleCase(column)) +
    scale_fill_discrete(name = "Wine quality") +
    theme_classic() +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 15, hjust = 0.5))
    
  hist_var<- ggplot(wine_nooutliers, aes(x = .data[[column]], fill = factor(quality))) +
    geom_histogram (alpha = 0.5,color = 'black') +
    ggtitle(paste("Distribution of ",toTitleCase(column))) +
    xlab(toTitleCase(column))+
    ylab ("Count") +
    scale_fill_discrete(name = "Wine quality") +
    theme_classic() +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 15, hjust = 0.5))
    
  gridExtra::grid.arrange(boxplot_var, hist_var, ncol = 1)

}


skew_kurt_cal <- function(data, variable_name) {
  skew <- skewness(data[[variable_name]])
  kurt <- kurtosis(data[[variable_name]])
  
  print(paste("Skewness of", toTitleCase(variable_name), ":", skew))
  print(paste("Kurtosis of", toTitleCase(variable_name), ":", kurt))
}

5.3 Correlation

To understand the correlation between the variables, a correlation analysis is conducted. Some variables demon-strated a higher correlation with quality than others. Alco-hol shows a positive correlation at 0.51, with quality as the number one physicochemical property, followed by Sul-phates with a 0.35 correlation score and Citric Acid with a 0.24 correlation. Volatile Acidity shows a negative correla-tion with quality, with a -0.39 correlation score. From a chemical perspective, this research also considered the correlation between the independent variables. Fixed Acid-ity positively correlates with Citric Acid (0.7) and Density (0.66). However, there’s no multicollinearity existed

5.4 t-test

Based on previous descriptive analysis, the median wine quality of the observations in this dataset is 6.0. Based on this fact, the dataset is in the bad (quality < 6) and the good quality group (quality >= 6). Before building the linear regression models, we performed an independent two-sample t-test to evaluate the difference in the four potential physical properties between the good and the bad wine better to understand the correlation between quality and physical properties. The four potential proper-ties studied in this t-test have the highest correlation coef-ficients with quality variables, including alcohol, sulfates, volatile acidity, and citric acid. In this test, the Null hypothesis states that the means are the same for the two quality groups. According to the four t-test results, we have sufficient evidence to prove significant differences in the means of the four property values between the bad and good quality groups at a 95% confidence level. The rejection of the null hypothesis above lays the foundation for further analysis.

6. Data Processing to meet model requirement

6.1. Assumptions

Assumption testing of linearity, additivity, and normality is essential to regression analysis, specifically for linear re-gression models. These assumptions serve as the founda-tion for the validity and reliability of regression results. This study found that the dataset met the additivity, lineari-ty, homogeneity, and homoscedasticity assumptions. However, with highly skewed data, the normality assump-tion still needs to be met. The insight led us to the neces-sary next step to normalize our variables.

6.2 Log Transformation of skewed data

With the understanding that most of the variables in this dataset are positively skewed, the log transformation method was chosen due to its ability to normalize highly skewed data. We chose the threshold of 0.5 to decide if a variable requires transformation. Chlorides and residual sugar are the most skewed variables.

wine_data_transformed <- wine_nooutliers
# To check again all of the variables are numeric
numeric_variables <- names(Filter(is.numeric, wine_data_transformed))

7. Data Modeling

7.1 Hypothesis testing

As the first step of modeling, the hypotheses of this study were set. The modeling process was conducted in the pur-pose of hypothesis testing. Null Hypothesis: There’s no significant relationship between wine quality and the physicochemical properties of the observations. Alternative Hypothesis: There’s a significant relationship between wine quality and the physicochemical properties of the observations.

7.3 Linear Regression Model

7.3.1 Model 1: Full model

This study uses the “stepwise regression” procedure for the best model. It’s a variable selection technique to identi-fy the best subset of predictor variables for a linear regres-sion model. The procedure involves systematically adding or removing variables based on specific criteria, such as adjusted R-squared, to arrive at the final model. TABLE 2 SKEWNESS AFTER DATA TRANSFORMATION

We chose the forward selection approach based on the correlation coefficients between the independent and de-pendent variables calculated above. We ran the linear re-gression models, adding the variables with the highest correlation with the dependent variable one by one and observing how the adjusted R-squared changes.

The metric we used to evaluate and compare models is R-squared (R2). R-squared measures the proportion of the variance in the response variable that is predictable from the input features. It indicates the goodness of fit of the model. The multiple R-squared is less reliable than the adjusted R-squared as it increases with the number of terms/ independent variables in the model. In contrast, the adjusted R-squared adjusts for the number of terms in the model or penalizes for excessive variables, providing a more accurate measure of the model’s goodness of fit. Adjusted R-squared increases mean the model explains a higher proportion of observation of Quality Score. On the other hand, if adding a variable lead to a decrease in ad-justed R-squared, it will be excluded from the regression model. This study explored 11 models with different combina-tions of variables. All 11 models show p-value < 2.2e-16 with adjusted R-squared ranging from 0.251 to 0.385. The model performed the best in terms of Adjusted R-squared is model 11, factoring in 9 variables out of the 11, includ-ing alcohol, volatile acidity, sulfates, total sulfur dioxide, chlorides, fixed acidity, pH, free sulfur dioxide, and citric acid. Though fixed acidity now shows a significant rela-tionship in terms of p-value (0.317), adding it in still in-creased the model’s explanatory power. [3] Thus, model 11 was chosen as the final model of this study.
The final model has a p-value of <2.2e-16. We reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative hypothesis since we have enough evidence to prove that the response variable can be explained by the model or, in other words, there is a significant relationship between the physico-chemical properties and wine quality sensory score. It shows that approximately 38.48% of the variation in Quality can be explained by the samples’ Alcohol, Volatile Acidity, Sulphates, Total Sulfur Dioxide, Chlorides, Fixed Acidity, pH, Free Sulfur Dioxide, and Citric Acid levels col-lectively.

Adjusted R-squared is the first metric this study consid-ered when picking the best model. ANOVA can be em-ployed to compare different models or treatments to de-termine the best fit for the data. To test and evaluate the data more systematically, we performed ANOVA testing. We picked models with the top 4 highest Adjusted R-squared to perform the comparison. The results showed that model 8 served as a baseline model, and models 9, 10, and 11 all have very low p-values.

The low p-values for the three models compared to the first model suggest that these three models have statisti-cally significant improvements in explaining the variance in the dependent variable compared to the first model. In other words, they offer a better overall fit.[4] However, the model with the lowest p-value is model 9, not model 11, with the highest adjusted R-squared. Given this situation, we have a trade-off between statistical sig-nificance and goodness of fit. Model 11 has a higher adjusted R-squared but not as low a p-value in the ANOVA test as model 9 because the model includes more independent variables with high p-values (>0.05 significant level), indicating that they do not make a statistically significant contribution independently. However, they may still collectively contribute to the mod-el’s explanatory power. We understand that the collective explanatory power of a set of independent variables can be more important than the significance of any single variable, especially when we are interested in understanding the overall relationship between the independent variables and the dependent variables and their inclusion in the model might still im-prove the overall predictive performance. Therefore, we chose model 11, with the highest adjust-ed R-squared of 0.3848, as the best model since it may capture more underlying patterns in the data. Understand-ing the overall relationship between these physicochemical properties and wine quality and improving the predictive performance helps us to understand how to improve the production process and deliver high-quality and consistent wine products to our customers.

7.5.2 Prediction and RMSE & MAE Calculation of final model

To further understand the predicting ability of the final model, this study performed a train-test split based on the transformed dataset. 80% of the observations in the da-taset were used as training sets and 20% as test sets. We trained the model using the training set and thus used the trained model to predict the quality in the test set. After-wards, the predicted quality and actual quality value in the test set are then compared, For this model validation, we evaluate the Mean Abso-lute Error (MAE) and Root Means Squared Error (RMSE) metrics: MAE calculates the average absolute differences between the predicted and actual values, RMSE measures the squared root of Mean Squared Error (MSE) which is the average of the squared differences between predicted and actual values, penalizes significant error and makes it sensitive to outliers. The lower the RMSE and MAE values, the better performance. The table… summarizes the RMSE and MAE calculation results of the three best models (model 9, model 10, and model 11) with the highest ad-justed-Rsquared. We only include these three models as they have been proven to have statistically significant im-provements compared to model 8. Since Model 11 pro-vides the lowest MAE of 0.4989 and RMSE of 0.6310 com-pared to the other two models, it has been proven to have the best predictive performance and confirms our choice of the best-fit model.

8.0 Conclusion

This thorough data analysis consists of Exploratory Data Analysis, Data Transformation, Modeling, Test and Evalua-tion. It helped us to understand what physicochemical properties contribute to high-quality wine. In particular, high alcohol, sulfates, and free sulfur dioxide containment are associated with high wine quality. On the other hand, low volatile acidity and pH are associated with high wine quality. Among these properties that stood out, we also called out there are correlations between Fixed Acidity and Citric Acid, which can suggest detailed control is required. In the view of a wine producer, the result of this study goes beyond a model with predicting ability. It also helps as a reference when making major investment decisions in the production process upgrade. For example, with this data analysis as proof, investments related to processes and equipment that help increase the level of alcohol, sul-fates, and free sulfur dioxide can be prioritized over other investment decisions. This study helps standardize the samples’ sensory scor-ing process for certification organizations. Since the score is gathered based on subjective evaluation of experienced wine tasters, having a data analytics approach to under-stand the universal physicochemical property component of recognized good wine helps to standardize high-quality wine and reduce human error in evaluation. Despite this study’s positive result and impact, the adjust-ed R-squared and Mean Absolute Error result remains rel-atively limited. Future work on more granular physico-chemical property measurement introducing more explanatory variables can be helpful for model improve-ment. Meanwhile, besides the multiple linear regression approach, we performed in this study, we believe that there are several advanced extensions of linear regression models that might be appropriate to our problem and da-ta, such as ridge regression and lasso regression, since they might provide insights into the influential factors that affect the quality outcome.

Furthermore, instead of using a linear-regression-based model, the non-linear relationship and interactions be-tween physicochemical properties and wine quality can be explored through decision-tree algorithms like Gradient Boosting Random Forests, as they are both ensembled learning methods with excellent predictive performance.
